Resultant Forces

Effects of Forces

A force is a push or a pull that acts on an object due to the interaction with another object. Forces can change an object's speed, direction, shape, or size. For example:

  • The thrust from an engine can change a car's speed.
  • The gravitational pull of the Sun can change a comet's direction.
  • Compression forces can change a spring's shape.

Balanced & Unbalanced Forces

The resultant force is the single force that has the same effect as all the other forces acting on an object.

Balanced Forces

If forces are balanced, the resultant force is zero. The object will either remain stationary or continue to move at a constant velocity.

Unbalanced Forces

If forces are unbalanced, there is a non-zero resultant force. The object will accelerate (change its speed or direction).

To calculate the resultant force on a straight line, you add forces acting in the same direction and subtract forces acting in opposite directions.

Scalars & Vectors

Scalars

Quantities that have only a magnitude (size).

  • Distance, Speed, Mass

Vectors

Quantities that have both magnitude and direction.

  • Displacement, Velocity, Force

Note: To find the resultant of two vectors not on a straight line, you can use a scale diagram. Two methods are the triangle method and the parallelogram method. Please refer to the diagrams for these methods in your notes.

Newton's First Law of Motion

An object will remain at rest, or move with a constant velocity, unless a resultant force acts upon it.

This law is also known as the Law of Inertia. Inertia is the tendency of an object to resist a change in its motion. The more mass an object has, the greater its inertia.

Example of Inertia

It is much harder to push a stationary car to get it moving than it is to push a stationary tennis ball. This is because the car has a much larger mass, and therefore a much greater inertia.

Newton's Second Law of Motion

This law links force, mass, and acceleration. The full definition is: "The resultant force on an object is proportional to its rate of change of momentum." For an object with constant mass, this simplifies to:

Resultant Force = mass x acceleration
F = m x a

One Newton (N) is the force required to give a mass of 1 kg an acceleration of 1 m/s¬≤.

Weight

Weight is the force of gravity on an object. Mass is the amount of 'stuff' in an object (measured in kg). Weight is a force (measured in N).

Weight = mass x gravitational field strength
W = m x g

On Earth, g is approximately 10 N/kg.

Investigating Force & Extension

This is a core practical to investigate the relationship between the force applied to a spring and its extension. (Please refer to the setup diagram in your notes).

Variables

  • Independent Variable: The Force applied (changed by adding masses).
  • Dependent Variable: The Extension of the spring (what you measure).
  • Control Variable: The original spring used (to ensure a constant spring constant).

Method Summary:

  1. Set up the apparatus with a clamp, spring, and ruler.
  2. Measure the original length of the spring.
  3. Add a known mass and calculate its weight (Force).
  4. Measure the new length of the spring.
  5. Calculate the extension (new length - original length).
  6. Repeat by adding more masses, recording force and extension each time.
  7. Plot a graph of Force (y-axis) against Extension (x-axis).

Analysis & Safety

Graph Analysis

A straight line through the origin shows force is directly proportional to extension. The gradient of this line is equal to the spring constant (k).

Safety Precautions

Wear safety goggles in case the spring snaps. Place a cushion or sand tray under the weights in case they fall.

Hooke's Law

The force needed to stretch a spring is directly proportional to the extension of the spring from its natural length.

Force = spring constant x extension
F = k x x

The spring constant (k) is a measure of the spring's stiffness, measured in N/m. A stiffer spring has a higher k value.

This relationship only holds true as long as the limit of proportionality (or elastic limit) is not exceeded. Beyond this point, the object is permanently deformed (inelastic deformation).

The Force-Extension Graph

The graph starts as a straight line through the origin (obeying Hooke's Law). After the limit of proportionality, the line begins to curve, showing that the same increase in force produces a much larger extension.

Circular Motion

An object moving in a circle at a constant speed has a constantly changing velocity. Why? Because its direction is always changing!

Since velocity is changing, the object is accelerating. This acceleration is caused by a resultant force called the centripetal force, which is always directed towards the center of the circle.

The size of the centripetal force required depends on:

  • The object's mass (more mass = more force)
  • The object's speed (more speed = more force)
  • The circle's radius (smaller radius = more force)

Friction

Friction is a force between two surfaces that opposes motion. It happens because surfaces are not perfectly smooth at a molecular level.

Friction (Solids)

Can be reduced by:

  • Lubricating the surfaces
  • Smoothing the surfaces

Friction in Fluids (Drag)

Gases and liquids are fluids. Friction in fluids is called drag (e.g., air resistance).

To reduce drag, objects are given a streamlined shape.

Air resistance reduces the speed of an object and can cause heating due to the work done against the force.

Example of Heating

The return module of a rocket heats up and glows as it re-enters the atmosphere. This is due to the intense work done against air resistance as it travels at high speed.
